👉 Life Cycle of a Thread

+-----------+      
| New       |
+-----------+
      ⇩ 
+-----------+-----------+
| Runnable  |           ⇩
+-----------+    +------------------------+
      ⇩          | Non Runnable (Blocked) |  
+-----------+    +------------------------+
| Running   |           ⇧
+-----------+-----------+
      ⇩ 
+------------+      
| Terminated |
+------------+

1. New State : Thread t = new Thread();

Thread object is created using new
But it has not started yet
It’s just ready to be started

2. Runnable State : t.start();

When you call start(), thread enters Runnable
It is ready to run, waiting for CPU
Important:
Runnable ≠ Running
It means “eligible to run”

3. Running State : public void run() {// code executes here}

Thread gets CPU and starts executing run()
Only one thread runs at a time per CPU core

4. Non-Runnable (Blocked State) : Thread.sleep(1000);

Thread temporarily stops running
Reasons:
            sleep()
            wait()
            Waiting for I/O
            Waiting for a lock
After condition is satisfied → goes back to Runnable

5. Terminated State :

Thread finishes execution
run() method ends
Thread is now dead and cannot restart

👉 Real-Life Analogy 🚦

New → You bought a car
Runnable → Waiting at signal
Running → Driving
Blocked → Traffic jam / red light
Terminated → Reached destination
